A powerful cyclone struck Bangladesh's southwestern coast, causing severe damage to property and infrastructure.
The storm, named Cyclone Sidr, brought extreme winds and torrential rain, leading to the evacuation of thousands of people from vulnerable coastal areas.
The United States and Germany offered emergency relief aid to assist in the recovery efforts.
The cyclone left a trail of devastation, with at least 41 people dead and hundreds of thousands displaced.
International organizations like the World Food Program allocated food supplies to help the victims.
The focus is on saving lives and providing essential support during this crisis.
